    public Element prepend(String html) {
        Validate.notNull(html);
        
        Element fragment = Parser.parseBodyFragment(html, baseUri).body();
        List<Node> fragmentNodes = fragment.childNodes();
        List<Node> nodes = new java.util.ArrayList<Node>();
        for (Node node : fragmentNodes) {
            if (node instanceof Element && this.tag() != null && ((Element) node).tag() != null) {
                Element el = (Element) node;
                if (this.tag().getName().equals("table") && el.tag().getName().equals("table")) {
                    // unwrap the implicit table
                    for (Node child : el.childNodes()) {
                        child.parentNode = null;
                        nodes.add(child);
                    }
                    continue;
                }
            }
            node.parentNode = null;
            nodes.add(node);
        }
        // Now prepend in reverse order to maintain original order
        for (int i = nodes.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            prependChild(nodes.get(i));
        }
        return this;
    }
```

Note: In prepend, we need to maintain the order of the fragment. The original code iterated fragment.childNodes() in reverse order and prepended each, which results in the fragment's children appearing in the same order as in the HTML after prepending. Our new approach: we collect all nodes to be added in `nodes` in the order they appear in the fragment (after unwrapping). Then we prepend them in reverse order so that the first node in the fragment ends up being the first after prepending. That matches the original logic.

